snippet.textDisplay: I love this channel! I will say however, that I have to roll my eyes a bit during this video (and others) that allude to the animals' suffering. It seems like the tendency to project human emotions and needs onto these animals is a very strong one. Cows and chickens do not have the same emotional or physical needs as us. Most dairies keep their livestock very healthy (on the whole) as this will naturally be more profitable for them. Animals change their behavior when they are distressed and a cow will stop producing milk if it is sick or distressed. I just wanted to point out that I can see the 'environmental impact' angle, but the 'human-level suffering' angle is more than a bit of a stretch for me. The people who fall for this idea probably only mainly interact with dogs and cats, which are animals leaps and bounds more intelligent and complex than cows or chickens (which should be obvious as they are predatory animals, not prey animals), and even dogs and cats have markedly different social and physical needs than humans do.

snippet.textDisplay: Conventional dairy in the USA is harmful if you ask me. Cattle are fed a mix of GMO corn, grains, synthetic vitamins and antibiotics. Many growth hormones have been reported harmful to us and the animals and are banned in 30 countries. Some hormones have been shown to increase IGF-1 which has been attributed to causing cancer. The hormone rbST is injected make cows produce greater amounts of milk. These hormones cause mastitis hence why cows are treated with antibiotics. In fact in 2011 the FDA reported 80% of antibiotics in the US are used in agriculture. 10% of these antibiotics are penicillin. As well, the use of antibiotics is linked to allergies and leaky gut. Cow's milk is also high in omega 6. Furthermore, if you read about the farmer suicides in India, most of it is linked to how livestock are sick and dying from GMOs. It's more expensive to use these chemicals and GMO seeds, yet Monsanto sold it as this miracle that will feed the world. I implore people to do some research and buy organic grass-fed milk. Don't support the chemical companies and fall for paid lobbyists' biased research.
